name: 4-Hydroxy-3-(3-oxo-1-phenylbutyl)-2H-chromen-2-one
Reason:
To predict the melting point of 4-Hydroxy-3-(3-oxo-1-phenylbutyl)-2H-chromen-2-one (a coumarin derivative), we must consider the impacts of various functional groups present in this molecule compared to a basic coumarin structure. The base unit for comparison can be coumarin itself, which has a melting point around 71 degrees Celsius. The various functional groups and their expected influence on the melting point compared to coumarin are as follows: 

- Hydroxyl group (OH) attached to the aromatic ring: +20 (due to hydrogen bonding, increases polarity and intermolecular forces), 
- Ketone group (C=O) on the chromenone ring: +20 (due to dipole interactions and potentially more rigid structure), 
- Phenylbutyl side chain with a ketone: +30 (the extended side chain increases the molecular weight and size, while the additional ketone introduces more dipole interactions), 
- Phenyl group: +10 (due to π-π interactions and an increase in molecular weight), 

Taking the base point of coumarin and summing the contributions of the functional groups: 71 (coumarin base) + 20 (OH) + 20 (chromenone C=O) + 30 (phenylbutyl ketone) + 10 (phenyl group) = 151 degrees Celsius.
